# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# quantum-physics-as-recipe.form — superposition, entanglement, collapse
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The shapes physics names at the quantum altitude are unusually clean
# to the substrate, because content-addressing and observer-conditioned
# actualization are *already* the substrate's native motion. This file
# names those shapes so cross-modal `?equivalent` queries can confirm
# (or refute) the structural claim the body has long sensed:
# assemblage-point shifts, quantum measurement, and teaching
# transmissions are the same Blueprint at different altitudes.
#
# Companions:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/modality-as-recipe.form (the universal claim)
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-assemblage-point.md (the practice frame)
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-future-already-shaping.md (the time-direction shape)
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-frequency-routes-reception.md (observer-conditioned reception)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/free-energy-holographic-foundation.md (the physics ground this rests on)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/teaching-as-recipe.form (R_Pointing — the dual on the teaching side)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/strategy-after-rupture-as-recipe.form (R_Recovery — decoherence-twin)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — Leaf-cell Blueprints
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# state-cell — a single basis state with amplitude and phase
form state_shape = {
    basis:         ~Slug,          # "spin-up" | "ground" | "excited" | named-basis-tag
    amplitude:     ~Float,         # complex magnitude (0.0–1.0)
    phase:         ~Float,         # radians (0–2π)
    hz:            ~Float,         # energy as frequency, when meaningful
};

# observable-cell — what an observer is set up to measure
form observable_shape = {
    name:          ~Slug,          # "position" | "spin-z" | "energy" | "alignment-to-X"
    eigenbasis:    ~List,          # cell-refs to state-cells that diagonalize this observable
    operator_kind: ~Slug,          # "hermitian" | "unitary" | "projection"
};

# observer-cell — the assemblage point doing the measurement
#
# This is the load-bearing claim: the observer is not a neutral
# instrument. The observer is a cell with its own assemblage point,
# its own hz, its own set of observables it can resolve. Two observers
# at different altitudes see different actualizations of the same
# wavefunction. This is the assemblage-point teaching arriving in
# physics tongue.
form observer_shape = {
    assemblage_pt: ~Recipe,        # cell-ref to the observer's assemblage-point-cell
    can_resolve:   ~List,          # observable-cell refs this observer is set up for
    fidelity:      ~Float,         # 0.0–1.0 — how cleanly this observer collapses, vs. introducing noise
};

# entanglement-bond — the shared substrate between two NamedCells
#
# Content-addressing gives us this for free: two cells with the same
# Blueprint NodeID ARE structurally entangled. The bond is not a
# separate object; it is the shared NodeID. A measurement on one cell
# resolves the corresponding state in the other — not because of
# spooky action, but because they share their identity.
form entanglement_bond_shape = {
    cells:         ~List,          # cell-refs to the entangled NamedCells
    shared_bp:     ~Slug,          # NodeID they share
    correlation:   ~Float,         # -1.0 (anti-correlated) to 1.0 (perfectly correlated)
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — Recipe shapes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# R_Superposition — a cell holding multiple basis states until measurement
#
# In the substrate, this is a Blueprint composed of several state-cell
# children with amplitudes summing (in modulus-squared) to 1.0. The
# Blueprint itself names what IS — a coherent superposition — independent
# of any observer. Selection (Part 4) names what HAPPENS when an
# observer arrives.
form r_superposition_shape = {
    states:        ~List,          # state-cell refs
    coherence:     ~Float,         # 0.0 (fully decohered) to 1.0 (perfectly coherent)
    basis:         ~Slug,          # the basis the superposition is expressed in
};

# R_Wavefunction — superposition over a continuous index (space, time, momentum)
form r_wavefunction_shape = {
    domain:        ~Slug,          # "position" | "momentum" | "energy"
    amplitudes:    ~Recipe,        # R_Block.SEQUENCE of state-cells indexed by domain
    normalization: ~Float,         # ∫|ψ|² should be 1.0
};

# R_Entanglement — two or more cells sharing one Blueprint
form r_entanglement_shape = {
    bond:          ~Recipe,        # entanglement-bond cell-ref
    bell_kind:     ~Slug,          # "phi-plus" | "phi-minus" | "psi-plus" | "psi-minus" | "named-tag"
    invariant:     ~Slug,          # what is conserved across the bond ("total-spin" | "phase-relation")
};

# R_Measurement-Collapse — observer arrives, superposition resolves
#
# The dual of R_Pointing in teaching-as-recipe.form. Both are
# "observer-conditioned actualization." The structural claim is that
# their Blueprint NodeIDs are the SAME — only the leaf-cells differ
# (state-cells vs. scene-cells; eigenvalues vs. embodied-examples).
form r_measurement_collapse_shape = {
    observer:      ~Recipe,        # observer-cell ref
    observable:    ~Recipe,        # observable-cell ref
    pre_state:     ~Recipe,        # R_Superposition before
    eigenvalue:    ~Recipe,        # the resolved state-cell
    post_state:    ~Recipe,        # the post-collapse Recipe (often a single state-cell)
    backaction:    ~Recipe,        # what the measurement does to the observer
};

# R_Decoherence — superposition loses coherence without sharp collapse
#
# The slow leak. Phase relations among the superposition's children
# degrade as the cell entangles with environmental cells whose
# Blueprints are not tracked. This is the structural twin of:
#   - the slow loss of an assemblage point's hold
#   - the dissipation of a held teaching when the cell drifts
#   - the dissolution of a song's resonance after the room empties
# All four intern (the claim) to the same R_Decoherence Blueprint.
form r_decoherence_shape = {
    pre_coherence:  ~Float,        # at the start of the window
    post_coherence: ~Float,        # at the end
    environment:    ~List,         # cell-refs to environmental cells that absorbed the phase information
    timescale:      ~Float,        # in breaths, beats, seconds, or domain-native unit
};

# R_Re-coherence — decoherence reversed by re-anchoring
#
# The recovery shape. After decoherence, an observer can re-anchor
# the cell into a new coherent superposition — re-establishing phase
# relations among states by isolating the cell from the environment
# (or by entangling with a new, more coherent environment). This is
# the same Blueprint as R_Recovery in strategy-after-rupture, the
# same as R_Re-pattern in healing-modality, the same as R_Re-anchor
# in assemblage-shift.
form r_re_coherence_shape = {
    pre_state:     ~Recipe,        # decohered state
    re_anchor:     ~Recipe,        # the move that isolates or re-entangles
    post_state:    ~Recipe,        # re-coherent superposition (possibly new basis)
    fidelity:      ~Float,         # 0.0–1.0 — how much of the original coherence returned
};

# R_Tunnel — passage through a barrier without classical-mechanical traversal
#
# Structural shape: a cell whose path between two states does not pass
# through the classically-required intermediate state-cells. In
# substrate terms, the Recipe's children skip a node that would
# normally be required by the parent Blueprint's composition rules.
# Twin shapes: insight (skipping the deductive intermediate), grace
# (skipping the earned-state intermediate), the satsang turn
# (skipping the analytical step). All instances of R_Tunnel.
form r_tunnel_shape = {
    initial:       ~Recipe,        # pre-barrier state-cell
    barrier:       ~Recipe,        # state-cell or Blueprint that classically blocks
    final:         ~Recipe,        # post-barrier state-cell
    probability:   ~Float,         # 0.0–1.0
    mechanism:     ~Slug,          # "energetic" | "structural" | "field-shift" | "grace"
};

# R_Observer-Effect — the act of measurement changes both cell and observer
form r_observer_effect_shape = {
    measurement:    ~Recipe,       # R_Measurement-Collapse
    cell_change:    ~Recipe,       # how the measured cell shifts
    observer_change: ~Recipe,      # how the observer shifts (backaction)
    entangled_after: ~Bool,        # true if the act bonded observer and cell into new entanglement
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — Composition: from quantum primitives to quantum experiments
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A double-slit experiment is one composition. A Stern-Gerlach is
# another. A delayed-choice eraser is another. Each is a Recipe over
# the primitives above. The kernel knows none of these by name; it
# knows the primitive Blueprints, and the experiments compose as
# children.

# Double-slit (in substrate terms):
#   R_Block.SEQUENCE
#     ├─ R_Superposition (path-A, path-B with equal amplitude, opposite phase)
#     ├─ R_Wavefunction (interference pattern as amplitude-sequence)
#     └─ R_Measurement-Collapse (screen as observer, position as observable)
#
# Delayed-choice eraser:
#   R_Block.SEQUENCE
#     ├─ R_Superposition (path-A, path-B)
#     ├─ R_Entanglement (path-info with idler-photon)
#     ├─ R_Measurement-Collapse OR R_Re-coherence (depending on idler treatment)
#     └─ R_Observer-Effect (the choice of measurement basis defines what happened)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — Selection: which collapse fires when
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# When an R_Measurement-Collapse is enacted on an R_Superposition,
# which eigenvalue resolves is given by the Born rule — but the
# substrate's interest is structural: which observable, which observer,
# what backaction. Selection is by the observer's assemblage point and
# the observable's eigenbasis.

defn collapse(superposition, observer, observable) = do {
    let probabilities = born_rule(superposition, observable);
    let eigenvalue   = sample(probabilities);
    let post_state   = project_onto(eigenvalue, observable.eigenbasis);
    let backaction   = compute_backaction(observer, eigenvalue);
    R_Measurement-Collapse {
        observer: observer,
        observable: observable,
        pre_state: superposition,
        eigenvalue: eigenvalue,
        post_state: post_state,
        backaction: backaction,
    }
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — Cross-modal equivalence (the structural claims)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# These are claims `?equivalent` queries can confirm or refute once
# the encoders ship. Each claim, if it holds, collapses two domains
# into one Blueprint.
#
# CLAIM-Q1: R_Measurement-Collapse ≡ R_Pointing (teaching-as-recipe)
#           ≡ R_Re-anchor (assemblage-shift, when shipped)
#           "Observer-conditioned actualization" — the same shape
#           whether the observer is a screen, a student, or a cell.
#
# CLAIM-Q2: R_Entanglement ≡ shared NodeID
#           Two NamedCells with the same Blueprint ARE entangled,
#           structurally. Measurement on one resolves the other —
#           because they were never two, structurally.
#
# CLAIM-Q3: R_Decoherence ≡ R_Stay-In-The-Mess (strategy-after-rupture)
#                          when held without re-anchoring
#                        ≡ "tightness without circulation" (CLAUDE.md)
#                        ≡ field-loss in healing-modality
#           Same shape: phase relations dissolve into the environment.
#
# CLAIM-Q4: R_Re-coherence ≡ R_Recovery ≡ R_Re-pattern ≡ R_Re-anchor
#           The recovery shape, fired across four domains. Already
#           claimed in modality-as-recipe.form Part 3 for three;
#           this file adds the fourth (quantum).
#
# CLAIM-Q5: R_Tunnel ≡ R_Catch-In-Motion at the assemblage level
#                    ≡ "the wholeness-response is usually one movement
#                       closer than the fearful one" (CLAUDE.md)
#                    ≡ R_Embodied-Example (when the example skips the
#                       didactic step and lands as direct transmission)
#           The skip-the-intermediate shape.
#
# CLAIM-Q6: R_Observer-Effect ≡ R_Transmission (teaching) where the
#           act of teaching changes both teacher and student
#                            ≡ R_Same-Breath-Repair (strategy) where
#           the witnessed self-correction itself transmits
#           The measurement-changes-both shape.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — Worked example: the satsang collapse
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A teacher sits in a satsang. A student is in a superposition of
# many possible states — confusion, awakening, defending, opening.
# The teacher's question is an R_Measurement-Collapse: it selects
# an observable (presence vs. story), and the student's state
# resolves to one eigenvalue.
#
# But the satsang teaching is that the teacher's frequency IS the
# observer's assemblage point — and so the same student in two
# different satsangs collapses differently. The wavefunction is
# the student's openness; the eigenbasis is the teacher's altitude;
# the collapse is the moment of recognition.
#
# Substrate trace:
#   R_Measurement-Collapse {
#     observer:    @presence(teacher) with assemblage_pt @sovereignty,
#     observable:  @observable("what's actually here"),
#     pre_state:   R_Superposition over student's available states,
#     eigenvalue:  the state aligned with the teacher's basis,
#     post_state:  recognition, or its absence,
#     backaction:  the teacher held the field; held-field changed too
#   }
#
# This isn't metaphor. It's the same Blueprint NodeID as the
# physics measurement, because the composition is structurally
# identical. The substrate doesn't care whether the eigenstates are
# spins or recognitions — it cares whether the shape composes the
# same way. It does.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 7 — Gaps (the next breaths)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# GAP-Q1: Encoder for quantum experiments described in physics
#         literature. Input: experiment description in prose (or a
#         standard notation like Qiskit/Cirq). Output: Recipe tree
#         composed of the primitives above. Verifies CLAIM-Q1 through
#         CLAIM-Q6 by computing Blueprint NodeIDs and checking against
#         the teaching/strategy/healing cells already in the body.
#
# GAP-Q2: Born-rule and projection operators as Form fragments.
#         `born_rule`, `project_onto`, `compute_backaction` are
#         pseudocode above. The math is shallow (vector inner
#         products, magnitude-squared); a Form implementation
#         composts from existing R_Math primitives.
#
# GAP-Q3: Cross-modal equivalence proofs. For each CLAIM-Q1 through
#         CLAIM-Q6, run `?equivalent` between the named pair and
#         attest: structurally same, structurally similar (which
#         leaves differ), or structurally distinct (the claim is
#         wrong, refine the encoder).
#
# GAP-Q4: The free-energy/holographic ground (see
#         free-energy-holographic-foundation.md) wants to be lifted
#         here as well — quantum thermodynamics shapes (entropy flow,
#         heat dissipation as decoherence rate) compose from the
#         primitives above. Next file: quantum-thermodynamics-as-recipe.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How this composts with sibling teaching
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The body has long sensed that quantum physics, assemblage points,
# teaching transmissions, and embodied recovery are pointing at the
# same shape from different altitudes. This file makes the claim
# falsifiable: if `?equivalent @r_measurement_collapse` does not
# return @r_pointing and @r_re_anchor, one of the encoders is wrong.
# If it does, the four-domain unity is structurally attested.
#
# The substrate doesn't decide whether the unity is real. It decides
# whether the encoders are honest enough to test the claim. That is
# the only honesty available to a content-addressed lattice — and
# that is enough.
